SYS1 Patch Suggestions for LS-DOS 6.3 from M. A. D. Software	18-Jul-93The following patches eliminate the extra blank lines that LS-DOSinserts before and after each command line and changes the command prompt tosomething more compact.The patches are not required to be able to use the tools enclosed on thisdisk.  The PIPES(U1) utility temporarily applies patch #1 in RAM (not to thefile on your disk) and removes the patch when PIPES(U1) finishes executing.If you apply patch #1, that change becomes permanent and PIPES(U1) will notremove it.Using these patches is completely optional and entirely up to you.Patch #1 eliminates the blank line that follows the command line.PATCH SYS1/SYS.SYSTEM6:0 (D00,DE=00 00 00:F00,DE=CD 42 06)Patch #2 eliminates the blank line in front of the command line prompt andchanges the prompt from "LS-DOS Ready" to "#> ", which shares thecommand line with the typed command.  This uses the screen more efficiently.PATCH SYS1/SYS.SYSTEM6:0 (D05,15=0E 1E 23 3E 20 03:F05,15=0A 0E 4C 53 2D 44)An alternate prompt, "% " can be obtained with this patch (Patch #2B):PATCH SYS1/SYS.SYSTEM6:0 (D05,15=0E 1E 25 20 03:F05,15=0A 0E 4C 53 2D)You may apply patch 1 and/or patch 2A or patch 2B if you desire.  If you electto remove the patches, simply reload SYS1/SYS from an older copy (we stronglyrecommend that you never patch your original distribution diskette), orexchange the values in the 'D' and 'F' sections of each patch.The OOPS(U1) utility has been modified to skip the prompt if it appearson the command line.  OOPS(U1) does require that the prompt not contain anyletters in upper or lowercase.  An older version of OOPS(U1) that isincluded with other M. A. D. Software products does not understand promptson the line being edited and should be replaced with this newer version.These patches are not from MISOSYS and are not official.  If you encountertrouble with LS-DOS, you should replace SYS1/SYS with an unmodifiedcopy to verify that these patches are not the cause of the difficulty.Finally, these patches were meant for LS-DOS 6.3.x, and may not be usableon other versions.307182